article.description: Deanna Nolan made a jumper with 2.2 seconds remaining to give the Detroit Shock a 58-57 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on Saturday night. Nolan hit a similar shot with one second left to beat Indiana 70-68 on Wednesday.
article.headline: Nolan knocks off Rockers with jumper
article.linkText: Nolan delivers again late for Shock
article.story:
CLEVELAND (AP) -- Deanna Nolan got the ball and won the game --
again.

Nolan made a jumper with 2.2 seconds remaining to give the
Detroit Shock a 58-57 victory over the Cleveland Rockers on
Saturday night. Nolan hit a similar shot with one second left to
beat Indiana 70-68 on Wednesday.

"It was a set play," Nolan said. "It was designed for me to
hopefully get open and make the shot. Hopefully, and luckily the
shot went in."

Trailing 57-56 with 7.8 seconds left, Shock coach Bill Laimbeer
called a timeout to set up the play. Nolan drove around a pick on
the right wing and hit a 14-foot shot.

"She is one of the few players in this league who can create
her shot at any given time," Laimbeer said. "It was a set play
for her to come off a high pick-and-roll and you saw what she can
do."

LaToya Thomas missed an off-balance, 3-point attempt for
Cleveland as the final buzzer sounded.

"How about that shot?" Laimbeer said after the ball rattled
off the rim. "Whew!"

Swin Cash had a team-high 14 points, and Cheryl Ford had 11
points and 15 rebounds for the Shock, who have won three straight
and four of five.

Chasity Melvin, Merlakia Jones and Penny Taylor each scored 12
for the Rockers, who have alternated losses and wins the last nine
games.

Cash made the second of two free throws to give Detroit a 56-55
lead with 2:49 to play, but Deanna Jackson hit a 12-foot jumper to
put Cleveland up 57-56 with 2:02 left.

On three consecutive Shock possessions, Cleveland's defense
forced a 30-second violation, another turnover on a bad pass, and
got the ball yet again when Chasity Melvin blocked a layup attempt
by 6-foot-5 center Ruth Riley.

"We really battled," Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. "They
hadn't made a field goal over the last five minutes until Nolan hit
that shot."

Cleveland couldn't convert its shots, however.

Nolan finished with eight points.

"Give her credit," Jones said. "We knew the play they were
going to run and defensively we were there. She just made a great
shot."

Both teams were without key players for long stretches. Thomas,
the first pick in this year's WNBA draft, left in the first half
with abdominal cramps and did not return until the final seconds.
She scored two points in eight minutes.

Taylor missed the final 4:34 after being cut in her mouth during
a collision with Cash, who was called for traveling.

Detroit center Riley, averaging 9.5 points a game, got into
quick foul trouble and had only two points in 15 minutes.

"We put ourselves in a great situation to beat that team,"
Hughes said. "The difference I see is the free throw line. We just
didn't get there enough."

The Shock made 14 of 21 free throws compared to just six of nine
for Cleveland.
